Interview Questions

Q1. What is the Queue interface in Java?
-->Queue is an interface in the Java Collections Framework that represents a collection designed to hold elements before processing them.
It generally follows the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle, where the first element inserted is the first one removed.
      
      Characteristics
      Follows FIFO order (except PriorityQueue).
      Does not support index-based access.
      Generally does not allow null elements.
      Supports insertion, deletion, and retrieval from both ends depending on the implementation.
      
      Example:
      
      import java.util.*;
      
      public class Demo {
          public static void main(String[] args) {
      
              Queue<String> queue = new LinkedList<>();
      
              queue.offer("A");
              queue.offer("B");
              queue.offer("C");
      
              System.out.println(queue);
          }
      }
      
      Output
      
      [A, B, C]




Q2. Does Queue allow null elements? Explain.
-->Generally, No.

      Most Queue implementations, such as PriorityQueue and ArrayDeque, do not allow null elements.
      
      This is because methods like poll() return null to indicate that the queue is empty. Allowing null elements would make it impossible 
      to distinguish between an actual null element and an empty queue.
      
      Note: LinkedList (when used as a Queue) technically allows null, but it is discouraged because it can lead to ambiguity.



Q3. What are the common Queue implementations?
-->The commonly used Queue implementations are:

      1. LinkedList
            Implements Queue and Deque.
                Follows FIFO order.
                Suitable for general-purpose queue operations.
      2. PriorityQueue
            Elements are processed based on priority.
            Maintains natural ordering or uses a custom Comparator.
            Does not follow FIFO.
      3. ArrayDeque
            Implements Deque.
              Faster than Stack and LinkedList for queue and stack operations.
              Does not allow null elements.
| Implementation | Order               | Null Allowed      |
| -------------- | ------------------- | ----------------- |
| LinkedList     | FIFO                | Yes (discouraged) |
| PriorityQueue  | Priority-based      | No                |
| ArrayDeque     | FIFO / Double-ended | No                |




Q4. On which principle does a Queue work in Java?
-->A Queue generally works on the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle.

The first element inserted into the queue is the first one removed.

Example:

import java.util.*;

public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Queue<Integer> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        queue.offer(10);
        queue.offer(20);
        queue.offer(30);

        System.out.println(queue.poll());
        System.out.println(queue.poll());
    }
}

Output

10
20

      The element 10 was inserted first, so it is removed first.



      Interview Tip
          TreeSet → Sorted order, unique elements, backed by a Red-Black Tree, no null values.
          Queue → Generally follows FIFO, used for processing elements in insertion order.
          LinkedList → FIFO queue implementation.
          PriorityQueue → Processes elements based on priority, not insertion order.
          ArrayDeque → Efficient implementation of both Queue and Stack operations.
